## SECTION 7 — REMEDIATION

### 7.1 Immediate actions

{% if risk.overall in ("CRITICO", "ALTO") %}
1. Isolate the system from the network if there is confirmed evidence of active compromise.
2. Revoke and rotate all credentials that had access to the system.
3. Notify the incident response team with this report.
4. Preserve additional evidence before any changes to the system.
5. Review other systems in the same network segment.
{% else %}
1. Review identified findings and initiate remediation process.
2. Increase logging level and log retention.
3. Review SSH access policy and authentication controls.
{% endif %}

### 7.2 Corrective actions per finding

{% for finding in findings %}
{% if finding.severity in ("critical", "high", "medium") %}
**[{{ finding.rule_id }}] {{ finding.title }}:**
{{ finding.recommendation }}

{% endif %}
{% endfor %}

### 7.3 Preventive hardening

- Enable SSH key authentication and disable password authentication.
- Configure fail2ban or equivalent for automatic IP blocking on multiple failures.
- Restrict SSH access by source IP at the firewall.
- Review and minimize sudo privileges (principle of least privilege).
- Configure logrotate with at least 90 days retention.
- Enable auditd for monitoring critical system calls.
- Review and clean user and system crontabs.
- Update the operating system and all installed packages.

### 7.4 Recommended monitoring

- Implement SIEM or log centralization (rsyslog/syslog-ng to central server).
- Alerts on: multiple authentication failures, off-hours access, sudo usage.
- File integrity monitoring (AIDE, Tripwire) on critical paths.
- Periodic review of user accounts and authorized SSH keys.

