## SECTION 8 — LIMITATIONS AND WARNINGS

### 8.1 Technical limitations

- **Host key verification omitted:** Server authenticity was not verified
  cryptographically. In high-criticality contexts, verify via alternative channel.

- **Limited time window:** This analysis covers exclusively the last
  {{ report_metadata.time_window_hours }}h of available log activity.
  Earlier activity may not be covered.

- **Compressed or rotated logs:** Logs rotated by logrotate were collected
  when accessible (see manifest for complete list of acquired artifacts).

- **Access without elevated privileges:** If the operator connected with a non-root user,
  some system logs may not have been accessible (journalctl may require
  membership in the systemd-journal group).

{% if acquisition.errors %}
- **Commands failed during acquisition:** {{ acquisition.errors | length }} command(s)
  could not be executed. See Section 2.4 for details.
{% endif %}

### 8.2 Possible false positives

- Legitimate monitoring tools can generate patterns similar to scans.
- Automation scripts (Ansible, Puppet, Chef) can generate multiple
  authentications in a short time.
- Users with dynamic IPs can generate authentication alerts due to IP changes.

### 8.3 Analytical uncertainties

- Findings with MEDIUM or LOW confidence require manual validation before
  taking containment actions.
- Absence of findings does not guarantee absence of compromise; a sophisticated
  attacker may have cleaned logs or acted outside the analyzed time window.
- Correlation between services may be incomplete if some logs were not available.

